# TAMS — System Requirements Specification Guide

Template structure: `docs/templates/software_requirement_specification_template.md`
Output file: `docs/official/system-requirements.md`

Also follow `documentation-standards.mdc`. Assign `FR-*` IDs to each system-wide functional requirement.

## Introduction

Define scope (transcript upload, parse, graduation evaluation, rule management including category-course cohort bounds, auth), reference documents (`docs/official/vision.md`, `docs/architecture.md`, `docs/category-course-cohort-bounds.md`), and glossary terms: PII, ECTS, graduation category, curriculum equivalence, enrollment cohort, category-level cohort bounds, course-level cohort bounds, enrollment term (GUZ/BAHAR).

## System-Wide Functional Requirements

Requirements **not** expressed as use cases. Each item gets an `FR-*` ID.

| ID | Requirement | Source |
|----|-------------|--------|
| FR-AUTH-001 | JWT-based authentication with access and refresh token rotation | `auth-service` |
| FR-AUTH-002 | Role-based access control (ADMIN, TEACHER, STUDENT) | `auth-service`, `AppRouter.tsx` |
| FR-SYS-001 | Health check endpoints on every service (`/actuator/health` or `/health`) | All services |
| FR-SYS-002 | Rate limiting at api-gateway during peak load | `api-gateway` |
| FR-SYS-003 | Database schema versioning via Flyway migrations | Spring Boot services |
| FR-SYS-004 | Structured logging without PII in log output | All services |

Add more from code as needed; do not invent unimplemented requirements.

## System Qualities

### Usability

- Turkish user-visible strings in the frontend; English for code and formal docs.
- shadcn/ui design system per `ui-design.mdc`: slate palette, rose accent, Inter typography.
- Role-specific navigation shells (`AppShell.tsx`, `AppRouter.tsx`).
- Loading skeletons and error states on all data-fetching views.

### Reliability

- Kafka message retry and error handling for parser pipeline.
- Kubernetes/Docker health probes on all services.
- PostgreSQL persistence for auth, rules, and analysis data.
- Parser failure surfaced to analysis-service with user-visible error.

### Performance

- Synchronous API endpoints respond within acceptable web latency (state target, e.g., < 2 s for CRUD).
- PDF parsing is async via Kafka; state expected parse duration as TBD if not measured.
- Kafka topic retention: `transcript.raw` 5 min, `transcript.parsed` 1 hr.

### Supportability

- Monorepo with shared Maven parent POM.
- All secrets and config via environment variables (`.env.example`).
- Multi-stage Dockerfiles, non-root runtime user.
- K8s manifests under `infrastructure/k8s/`.

## System Interfaces

### User Interfaces

#### Look & Feel

Slate neutral base, rose-700 primary accent, green/amber/red semantic states. Professional academic tool aesthetic; no decorative color use.

#### Layout and Navigation Requirements

- Admin area: `/admin/*` — dashboard, departments, courses, graduation categories, equivalence rules, users.
- Teacher area: transcript upload, analysis results, history.
- Student area: own result view only.
- Login and mandatory password change outside main shell.

#### Consistency

shadcn/ui components, react-hook-form + zod for all forms, consistent button/input placement and terminology across roles.

#### User Personalization & Customization Requirements

Content filtered by user role and teacher-student relationship; no user-configurable themes in MVP.

### Interfaces to External Systems or Devices

#### Software Interfaces

| System | Protocol | Purpose |
|--------|----------|---------|
| PostgreSQL (auth, rules, analysis) | JDBC | Persistent storage |
| Kafka KRaft | Kafka protocol | Async transcript parsing pipeline |
| parser-service | Kafka + HTTP | PDF parsing and PII masking |
| auth-service (internal) | HTTP | Token validation (`/internal/auth/validate`) |

#### Hardware Interfaces

None — browser-only client; server-side container deployment.

#### Communications Interfaces

HTTPS for client-to-gateway; internal service mesh or Docker network for inter-service calls.

## Business Rules

Organize by rule class. Each rule gets a `BR-*` ID. Use if-then or decision-table format.

Rule classes to cover (sources: `docs/graduation-rules-v2-architecture.md`, `docs/category-course-cohort-bounds.md`, `rule-service`, `analysis-service`):

- **Enrollment Cohort Rules (`BR-COHORT-*`)** — cohort derivation from registration date; category-level year-only skip; course-level year+term bounds with inclusive start and exclusive end; BAHAR/GUZ ordering; null term default; missing registration date behavior
- **Graduation Category Rules (`BR-GRAD-*`)** — credit/ECTS/course-count thresholds, mandatory courses (only when in cohort range)
- **Global Department Rules** — min total ECTS, fail-grade block
- **Conditional and Prefix Rules** — conditional threshold substitution, prefix sub-limits
- **Course Matching Rules (`BR-EQ-*`)** — curriculum equivalence expansion
- **Eligibility Evaluation Rules (`BR-ELIG-*`)** — overall graduation eligibility

Also include `FR-RULE-005` through `FR-RULE-007` for admin cohort-bound management and engine cohort derivation.

Example patterns:
- `BR-COHORT-007: If enrollment cohort is at or after appliesToYear+appliesToTerm, ignore the course assignment entirely (exclusive end).`
- `BR-GRAD-001: If earned credits in a category are below min_credit, mark the category unsatisfied.`

## System Constraints

- Java 21, Spring Boot 3.3.5, Python 3.12, Node.js 22.
- Naming conventions per `general.mdc` (kebab-case endpoints, dot-separated Kafka topics, snake_case DB tables).
- No hardcoded secrets; all sensitive values from environment variables.
- Every Dockerfile: multi-stage build, non-root user.

